author.name: Alisher Navoiĭ, 1441-1501

Mir Ali Šir

notesStmt.note: This is a Safavid illuminated and illustrated collection of the Ḫamse (quintet), written in Çaġatāy (eastern Turkic), composed by the celebrated ʿAlī Šīr Nevāʾī (d. 906 AH / 1501 CE), and inspired by the Persian Khamse of Niẓāmī and Amīr Khusraw Dihlavī. This copy dates to the tenth century AH / sixteenth CE and has five double-page illustrations in the early Safavid court style. Each double-page illustration introduces the following individual poems: Kitāb-i ḫeyrāt ül-ebrār (fols. 1b-2a), Kitāb-i Ferhād va Şīrīn (fols. 45b-46a), Kitāb-i Mecnūn va Leylā (fols. 108b-109a), Kitāb-i Heşt bihişt (fols. 147b-148a), and Kitāb-i Iskendernāme (fols. 199b-200a). Each poem is also introduced by an illuminated incipit (fols. 2b, 46b, 109b, 148b, and 200b). The brown goatskin binding has a central lobed oval with pendants and cornerpieces brushed with gold. It is possibly attributable to the tenth century AH / sixteenth CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Turkish.

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in blue, black, and gold

handDesc.handNote: Written in black nastaʿlīq script with red section headings

decoDesc.decoNote: Five double-page illustrations (fols. 1b-2a, 45b-46a, 108b-109a, 147b-148a, and 199b-200a); incipit pages with illuminated titlepieces (fols. 2b, 46b, 109b, 148b, and 200b); framing lines in blue, black, and gold

decoNote.title: A courtyard scene
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting a courtyard scene with courtiers carrying gifts.

decoNote.title: A courtyard scene
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting a courtyard scene with a prince receiving gifts. The inscription over the door on the left reads yā Mufattiḥ al-abwāb.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece introducing the first poem of the Ḫamse, inscribed Kitāb-i ḫeyrāt ül-ebrār.

decoNote.title: Khusraw being entertained in his court with wine and music
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Khusraw being entertained in his court with wine and music.

decoNote.title: Ferhād carrying Şīrīn and her dead horse on his shoulders
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Ferhād carrying Şīrīn and her dead horse on his shoulders.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece introducing the second poem of the Ḫamse, inscribed Kitāb-i Ferhād va Şīrīn.

decoNote.title: Leylā in her pavilion with her attendants
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Leylā in her pavilion with her attendants.

decoNote.title: Mecnūn in the company of wild animals
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece, depicting Mecnūn in the company of wild animals.

decoNote.title: Inicpit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece, introducing the third poem of the Ḫamse, inscribed Kitāb-i Mecnūn va Leylā.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr hunting deer while Fitnah plays the harp
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Bahrām Gūr hunting deer while Fitnah plays the harp.

decoNote.title: Bahrām Gūr being entertained by his maid
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Bahrām Gūr being entertained by his maid.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece introducing the fourth poem of the Ḫamse, inscribed Kitāb-i Heşt bihişt.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great at the side of Darius, the killed Persian king
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Alexander the Great (Iskender) at the side of Darius (Dārā), the killed Persian king.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great in search of the fountain of life
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated frontispiece depicting Alexander the Great (Iskender) in search of the fountain of life.

decoNote.title: Incipit page with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titlepiece introducing the fifth poem of the Ḫamse, inscribed Kitāb-i Iskendernāme.

binding.p: Possibly dates to the tenth century AH / sixteenth CE; brown goatskin (no flap); dentelle style with central lobed oval, pendants, and cornerpieces brushed with gold; doublures of a similar pattern decorated in gold and blue

history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters bequest
